## 9. HANDLING HEAVY LOAD & SCALING

### **Horizontal Scaling Strategy**
```
LOAD INCREASES
    │
    ▼
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│ Auto-scaling Triggers       │
├─────────────────────────────┤
│ CPU > 70%                   │
│ Memory > 80%                │
│ Request queue depth > 100   │
│ Response time > 500ms (p95) │
└─────────────────────────────┘
    │
    ▼
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│ Kubernetes Orchestration    │
├─────────────────────────────┤
│ • Spin up new pods          │
│ • Distribute load balancer  │
│ • Scale specific services   │
│ • Max replicas: 50          │
│ • Min replicas: 2           │
│ • Scale down after 10 min   │
└─────────────────────────────┘
```

### **Database Scaling**
```
Single Instance
    │
    ▼
Replica Set (Read Replicas)
    │
    ▼
Sharded Cluster (Horizontal Partitioning)
    │
    ├─ Shard 1: Users A-G
    ├─ Shard 2: Users H-P
    ├─ Shard 3: Users Q-Z
    └─ Auto-rebalancing enabled
```

### **Cache Scalability**
- Redis Cluster (automatic sharding)
- 3+ nodes minimum
- Auto-failover via Sentinel
- Persistent storage enabled

### **Load Balancing Strategy**
```
Round-Robin (simple)
    └─ Equal distribution

Least Connections (recommended)
    └─ Routes to server with fewest active connections

Resource-based
    └─ Routes based on CPU/memory

Geographic
    └─ Route to nearest data center
```

